#include <string>
using namespace std;

string convertMarkdownToHTML(string& markdown) {
    string html = "";
    bool inItalic = false; // to keep track of when <em> tags should be added

    // loop through each character in the markdown string
    for (int i = 0; i < markdown.length(); i++) {
        char c = markdown.at(i);

        // check for header (#) formatting
        if (c == '#') {
            // find the number of # symbols in a row
            int count = 0;
            while (i < markdown.length() && markdown.at(i) == '#') {
                count++;
                i++;
            }

            // add the appropriate <h> tag based on the number of # symbols
            html += "<h" + to_string(count) + ">";

            // skip the space after the # symbols
            while (i < markdown.length() && markdown.at(i) == ' ') {
                i++;
            }
        }

        // check for emphasis (*) formatting
        if (c == '*') {
            // if inItalic is true, that means we have already added an <em> tag
            // so we need to add a closing tag
            if (inItalic) {
                html += "</em>";
                inItalic = false;
            }
            // if inItalic is false, that means we have not yet added an <em> tag
            // so we need to add an opening tag
            else {
                html += "<em>";
                inItalic = true;
            }
        }

        // check for new line formatting
        if (c == '\n') {
            // if the previous character was also a new line, that means we are starting a new paragraph
            if (i > 0 && markdown.at(i-1) == '\n') {
                html += "</p><p>";
            }
            // otherwise, we just need to add a <br> tag
            else {
                html += "<br>";
            }
        }

        // otherwise, just add the character to the html string
        else {
            html += c;
        }
    }

    // add closing tags for any open tags at the end of the string
    if (inItalic) {
        html += "</em>";
    }
    html += "</h1>";

    return html;
}
```

Explanation:
The function starts by declaring an empty string to store the html formatted text and a boolean variable to keep track of when <em> tags should be added. Then, it loops through each character in the markdown string. 

For headers, it checks for the # symbol and counts how many there are in a row. Based on the number of # symbols, it adds the appropriate <h> tag to the html string. It also skips the space after the # symbols.

For emphasis, it checks for the * symbol. If the inItalic variable is true, that means an <em> tag has already been added and it adds a closing tag. If inItalic is false, that means no <em> tag has been added yet and it adds an opening tag.

For new line formatting, it checks for the \n character. If the previous character was also a new line, that means we are starting a new paragraph and it adds a closing and opening <p> tag. Otherwise, it just adds a <br> tag.

For all other characters, it just adds them to the html string.

At the end, it checks if inItalic is true and adds a closing <em> tag if necessary. It also adds a closing <h1> tag to complete the html string.

