To tell the type system in TypeScript that a value may have multiple types but will only have one in practice, you can use the type assertion syntax. This is done by using the "as" keyword followed by the type you want to assert the value to.

For example, if you have a variable named "value" that may have the types "string" or "number" but you know that it will always be a string, you can write:

let value: string | number = "Hello";
let newValue = value as string;

This tells the type system that the value should be treated as a string, even though it has the potential to also be a number.

Alternatively, you can also use the angle bracket syntax for type assertions:

let newValue = <string>value;

Both of these syntaxes are valid and achieve the same result. However, it is recommended to use the "as" keyword for type assertions in TypeScript.

