To draw a chessboard using FEN notation in LaTeX, we will first need to use the "chessboard" package. This package provides commands for creating and displaying chessboards.

To begin, we will need to declare the "chessboard" package in our document's preamble:

\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chessboard}

Next, we will need to specify the initial state of the chessboard using FEN notation. FEN stands for "Forsyth-Edwards Notation" and is a standard notation for describing the state of a chessboard. It uses a string of characters to represent the position of each piece on the board.

For example, let's say we want to draw a chessboard with the following FEN notation:

rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR

This notation represents the starting position of a standard chess game, with all pieces in their initial positions.

In LaTeX, we can use the command "\setchessboard" to specify the FEN notation and draw the chessboard:

\setchessboard{position=rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR}

This will create a standard-sized chessboard with the pieces in their starting positions. However, we can also customize the size and style of the chessboard using additional commands.

For example, we can use the command "\setboardfontcolors" to change the color of the board's squares:

\setboardfontcolors{whitefieldmask=gray, blackfieldmask=white}

This will make the white squares gray and the black squares white. We can also use the command "\setboardfontsize" to change the size of the board's squares:

\setboardfontsize{20pt}

This will make the squares larger and easier to see. Finally, we can use the command "\showboard" to display the chessboard in our document:

\showboard

The complete code for drawing a chessboard using FEN notation and customizing its appearance is as follows:

\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chessboard}

\begin{document}

\setchessboard{position=rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR}
\setboardfontcolors{whitefieldmask=gray, blackfieldmask=white}
\setboardfontsize{20pt}
\showboard

\end{document}

The output of this code will be a chessboard with the pieces in their starting positions, with the white squares gray and the black squares white, and with larger squares for better visibility:

rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR

This is just one example of drawing a chessboard using FEN notation in LaTeX. The "chessboard" package offers many other commands and options for customizing the appearance of the board, so feel free to explore and experiment with different settings to create your desired chessboard.

